    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2525274835" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2525274835" />
    <a title="Sue" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1019544-sue"><img alt="Sue" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513417264p2/1019544.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2525274835?book_show_action=true">Sep 10, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sue" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sue" href="/user/show/1019544-sue">Sue</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9781486233762" href="/book/show/26631442-straight">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2525274835&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2525274835" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14079523424000264946">Tightly written, this story romps along with action scenes cleverly interspersed with a mystery, interesting characters and the normal horse racing background. <br/><br/>Derek Franklin hears that his brother Greville has been seriously injured in an accident. He goes to the hospital and is there when his brother dies. He is mugged on the way out of the hospital and Greville&apos;s possessions are stolen. When he visits Greville&apos;s business he finds there has been a break-in, although nothing seems to have been </span>
  <span id="freeText14079523424000264946" style="display:none">Tightly written, this story romps along with action scenes cleverly interspersed with a mystery, interesting characters and the normal horse racing background. <br /><br />Derek Franklin hears that his brother Greville has been seriously injured in an accident. He goes to the hospital and is there when his brother dies. He is mugged on the way out of the hospital and Greville's possessions are stolen. When he visits Greville's business he finds there has been a break-in, although nothing seems to have been stolen. This is surprising given that Greville was a gemologist and kept thousands of semi-precious stones on the premises. He then goes to Greville's house to find that it has been burgled. It will give a good sense of the book to say that this all happens in the first few chapters! <br /><br />Derek is a jockey and has recently hurt his ankle in a riding accident. Dick Francis describes pain very well, without being unnecessarily gruesome about it. I was cringing as I read some of the passages describing how Derek carried on despite his injury, even riding a horse to display it to potential owners, well before he should have been riding again. Of course the background detail regarding the racing world is very good. I could feel the tension between the trainers, jockeys and owners, all of whom see their horse in a slightly different way.<br /><br />It's a complicated plot, which I won't go into in detail, but it was very convincing. I learned a lot about gemstones and the cutting of diamonds! I also enjoyed the descriptions of Greville's electronic gadgets. He had a gadget for everything and was obsessed with secrecy and security, understandable in his business. Derek had a hard time fathoming out what they were all for, or how to work them, but they helped him solve the mystery in the end. Naturally this part of the book has aged less well than some of the others. I can imagine some readers wouldn't ever have seen a micro-cassette in their lives! I smiled over Greville's portable car phone: Derek tried to use it to call his friend, who was driving the car for him, when he wanted to be picked up. The friend clearly didn't trust the phone and refused to answer it!<br /><br />The most moving parts were where Derek hears from so many people what a good man his brother had been. He also finds out that Greville had been following his career and was proud of his success as a jockey. They hadn't been particularly close and Derek begins to miss the brother he barely knew. I think many people could recognise this feeling of only appreciating someone after they are gone, and mourning for what might have been.<br /><br />The audio was narrated by Tony Britton. I liked his voice and he managed to do the women's voices successfully as well as the men's. This is a book I would happily read again.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14079523424000264946" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

